Stellar Prediction

In the field of astronomy, stellar classification involves categorizing stars according to their spectral characteristics. This classification system is crucial in understanding celestial objects. The initial cataloging of stars and their spatial distribution contributed to the realization that they constitute our Milky Way galaxy. As telescopes advanced, distinguishing Andromeda as a separate galaxy spurred the survey of numerous galaxies. The objective of this dataset is to classify stars, galaxies, and quasars by analyzing their spectral features.

Dataset

The dataset comprises 100,000 observations captured by the Sloan Digital Sky Survey (SDSS). Each observation is defined by 17 featurs and 1 classtype indicating whether it corresponds to a star, galaxy, or quasar.

  • obj_ID = Object Identifier, the unique value that identifies the object in the image catalog used by the CAS
  • alpha = Right Ascension angle (at J2000 epoch)
  • delta = Declination angle (at J2000 epoch)
  • u = Ultraviolet filter in the photometric system
  • g = Green filter in the photometric system
  • r = Red filter in the photometric system
  • i = Near Infrared filter in the photometric system
  • z = Infrared filter in the photometric system
  • run_ID = Run Number used to identify the specific scan
  • rereun_ID = Rerun Number to specify how the image was processed
  • cam_col = Camera column to identify the scanline within the run
  • field_ID = Field number to identify each field
  • spec_obj_ID = Unique ID used for optical spectroscopic objects
  • class = object class (galaxy, star or quasar object)
  • redshift = redshift value based on the increase in wavelength
  • plate = plate ID, identifies each plate in SDSS
  • MJD = Modified Julian Date, used to indicate when a given piece of SDSS data was taken
  • fiber_ID = fiber ID that identifies the fiber that pointed the light at the focal plane in eac observation

Goal

The primary goal for this project is to predict the class type of stellar via spectral characteristics captured, which is infact dealing with a classification problem and a clustering problem.n

Outlier detection
Since the data set is quite large, we perform the Local Outlier Factor algorithm to detect outlier samples.


















In[11]:






from sklearn.neighbors import LocalOutlierFactor
clf_lof = LocalOutlierFactor()
y_pred = clf_lof.fit_predict(x) 





















In[12]:






x_score = clf_lof.negative_outlier_factor_
outlier_score = pd.DataFrame()
outlier_score["score"] = x_score

























We set the threshold as the condition for being an outlier:


















In[13]:






threshold = np.quantile(x_score , .10)                                           
filtre2 = outlier_score["score"] < threshold
outlier_index = outlier_score[filtre2].index.tolist()

























We then remove the outlier points:


















In[14]:






df.drop(outlier_index, inplace=True)

Supervised Learning
Logistic Regression


















In[24]:






from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression

























Cross validation accuracy


















In[25]:






from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score

























We draw the cv-accuracy here:


















In[26]:






results = []
for max_iter in range(1, 4):
    clf_lr = LogisticRegression(multi_class='multinomial', solver='newton-cg', max_iter=max_iter*100)
    clf_lr.fit(x_train, y_train)
    test_acc = clf_lr.score(x_test, y_test)
    cv_acc = np.mean(cross_val_score(clf_lr, x_train, y_train, cv=10))
    results.append([max_iter, cv_acc])
results = pd.DataFrame(
    data=results,
    columns=['max_iter', 'cv accuracy'],
)





















In[27]:






sns.lineplot(
    x='max_iter',
    y='cv accuracy',
    data=results,
)

<Axes: xlabel='max_iter', ylabel='cv accuracy'>

Decision Tree

from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier

























We plot the cv-accuracy curve:


















In[32]:






results = []
for depth in range(6, 14):
    clf_dt = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=depth)
    clf_dt.fit(x_train, y_train)
    test_acc = clf_dt.score(x_test, y_test)
    cv_acc = np.mean(cross_val_score(clf_dt, x_train, y_train, cv=10))
    results.append([depth, cv_acc])
results = pd.DataFrame(
    data=results,
    columns=['depth', 'cv accuracy'],
)
